The side ranked eighth on the points table is one victory away from equalling the wins-tally of the side ranked second. This encapsulates the margins of this IPL. With every team having one game remaining at the time of writing, LSG, ranked third, have 7 wins, and KKR, ranked seventh, have 6 wins. The two sides, however, have had a vastly different journey.   
   
LSG haven't had the best time with injuries, and have won some very close contests. They have had some ugly incidents off the field. And yet, like a gritty accumulator in fifty-over cricket, they've been consistently in the top four without anyone noticing.   
   
They've had a woefully out-of-form captain opening for them, a captain who then got injured, and replaced. They haven't had a whole lot of stability in their XI. And yet, players have put their hand up when required - most recently, Marcus Stoinis and Nicholas Pooran in the batting department, quietly digging Ws out of their graves.   
   
Their bowling hasn't been star-studded, but for most of the tournament, it has been reliable, and certainly not a liability. And when it has been, LSG's batters have put their hand up to finish the job, and make up for their shortcomings.   
   
KKR were the side handed the wooden spoon. They had the personnel, but even their star players were limited. Little did the world know, that the two-time champions would become quintessential scrappers, and dig up new stars. Shardul Thakur single-handedly took them to their first win, and Rinku Singh did the unthinkable to notch up their second.   
   
Since then, KKR have found out that one-man shows couldn't sustain them to the title, but they eventually got what they were looking for - consistency in their batting, with Nitish Rana and Rinku Singh leading the charge, and the prowess of Jason Roy and Venkatesh Iyer up top, who have blown hot and cold, but put their hand up when required. Their bowling, too, found their lost panache, with their spinners outplaying CSK in their own game, at their own den last weekend.   
   
In this case, the numbers hardly tell the full story, and the ranks, even less so. LSG have quietly gotten to the top and are on the verge of qualification, and KKR are on their way to scripting their own miracle. Their own underdog's tale. Destiny permitting, of course.
